				           User Management 

Add user: sudo adduser name or
          sudo -u / adduser name or
______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
	  

					Granting sudoers access

sudo vi /etc/sudoers   or
sudo echo "userName ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL"\sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/userName
________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
					Password related commands

sudo passwd userName = create password


*****sudo vi /etc/passwd = you can use this command to change the shell of a user. Reason behind this is, sometimes when switching from ec2-user to another user or host name for example when you do 
sudo su - jenkins, then you say
whoami, it still states that you are ec2-user instead of jenkins. This is because the password shell for the user is listed as /bin/false. It is supposed to be /bin/bash. You use the command sudo vi /etc/passwd to edit the specific shell for the user you want.


cat/etc/shadow = detail information about user password
cat/etc/pass= detail information about user
cat/etc/passwds = detail info about user passwords
/etc/ssh/sshd_config= ssh configuration details
grep -i simon/etc/passwd= greps all individuals withe name simon, passwords
cat list | grep -i simon
